        &#95;base value;                                                           \\
        using <a href="/docs/api/files/lib/lib/ir/safepointirverifier-cpp/#ae96315ee246bd4a509133af84c88c5e1">BaseType</a> = &#95;base;                                                \\
    &#125;;</>}>
YAML I/O does conversion based on types. But often native data types are just a typedef of built in intergral types (e.g. int). But the C++ type matching system sees through the typedef and all the typedefed types look like a built in type. This will cause the generic YAML I/O conversion to be used. To provide better control over the YAML conversion, you can use this macro instead of typedef. It will create a class with one field and automatic conversion operators to and from the base type. Based on BOOST&#95;STRONG&#95;TYPEDEF. <a href="#ab74df4ad631bb362ad7d41fd875f0481">More...</a>

        &#95;base value;                                                           \\
        using <a href="/docs/api/files/lib/lib/ir/safepointirverifier-cpp/#ae96315ee246bd4a509133af84c88c5e1">BaseType</a> = &#95;base;                                                \\
    &#125;;</>}>
YAML I/O does conversion based on types. But often native data types are just a typedef of built in intergral types (e.g. int). But the C++ type matching system sees through the typedef and all the typedefed types look like a built in type. This will cause the generic YAML I/O conversion to be used. To provide better control over the YAML conversion, you can use this macro instead of typedef. It will create a class with one field and automatic conversion operators to and from the base type. Based on BOOST&#95;STRONG&#95;TYPEDEF.

Definition at line <a href="#l01728">1728</a> of file <a href="/docs/api/files/include/include/llvm/include/llvm/support/yamltraits-h">YAMLTraits.h</a>.
</MemberDefinition>

</SectionDefinition>

<Link id="l01424" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1424"><Highlight kind="comment">///</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01425" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1425"><Highlight kind="comment">/// The Input class is used to parse a yaml document into in-memory structs</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01426" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1426"><Highlight kind="comment">/// and vectors.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01427" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1427"><Highlight kind="comment">///</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01428" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1428"><Highlight kind="comment">/// It works by using YAMLParser to do a syntax parse of the entire yaml</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01429" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1429"><Highlight kind="comment">/// document, then the Input class builds a graph of HNodes which wraps</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01430" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1430"><Highlight kind="comment">/// each yaml Node.  The extra layer is buffering.  The low level yaml</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01431" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1431"><Highlight kind="comment">/// parser only lets you look at each node once.  The buffering layer lets</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01432" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1432"><Highlight kind="comment">/// you search and interate multiple times.  This is necessary because</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01433" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1433"><Highlight kind="comment">/// the mapRequired() method calls may not be in the same order</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01434" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1434"><Highlight kind="comment">/// as the keys in the document.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01435" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1435"><Highlight kind="comment">///</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01436" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1436" lineLink="/docs/api/classes/input"><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight><Highlight kind="keyword">class </Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"><a href="/docs/api/classes/input/#a86258e41539d20c5f42e0d0d91a0dc4b">Input</a> : </Highlight><Highlight kind="keyword">public</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"> <a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/yaml/io/#af6a69e8083e27fcd02a6573b3d648f8d">IO</a> &#123;</Highlight></CodeLine>

<Link id="l01720" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1720"><Highlight kind="comment">/// YAML I/O does conversion based on types. But often native data types</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01721" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1721"><Highlight kind="comment">/// are just a typedef of built in intergral types (e.g. int).  But the C++</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01722" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1722"><Highlight kind="comment">/// type matching system sees through the typedef and all the typedefed types</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01723" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1723"><Highlight kind="comment">/// look like a built in type. This will cause the generic YAML I/O conversion</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01724" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1724"><Highlight kind="comment">/// to be used. To provide better control over the YAML conversion, you can</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01725" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1725"><Highlight kind="comment">/// use this macro instead of typedef.  It will create a class with one field</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01726" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1726"><Highlight kind="comment">/// and automatic conversion operators to and from the base type.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01727" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1727"><Highlight kind="comment">/// Based on BOOST&#95;STRONG&#95;TYPEDEF</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01728" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1728" lineLink="#ab74df4ad631bb362ad7d41fd875f0481"><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight><Highlight kind="preprocessor">#define LLVM&#95;YAML&#95;STRONG&#95;TYPEDEF(&#95;base, &#95;type)                                 \\</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01729" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1729"><Highlight kind="preprocessor">    struct &#95;type &#123;                                                             \\</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01730" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1730"><Highlight kind="preprocessor">        &#95;type() = default;                                                     \\</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01731" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1731"><Highlight kind="preprocessor">        &#95;type(const &#95;base v) : value(v) &#123;&#125;                                     \\</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01732" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1732"><Highlight kind="preprocessor">        &#95;type(const &#95;type &amp;v) = default;                                       \\</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01733" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1733"><Highlight kind="preprocessor">        &#95;type &amp;operator=(const &#95;type &amp;rhs) = default;                          \\</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01734" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1734"><Highlight kind="preprocessor">        &#95;type &amp;operator=(const &#95;base &amp;rhs) &#123; value = rhs; return &#42;this; &#125;      \\</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01735" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1735"><Highlight kind="preprocessor">        operator const &#95;base &amp; () const &#123; return value; &#125;                      \\</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01736" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1736"><Highlight kind="preprocessor">        bool operator==(const &#95;type &amp;rhs) const &#123; return value == rhs.value; &#125; \\</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01737" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1737"><Highlight kind="preprocessor">        bool operator==(const &#95;base &amp;rhs) const &#123; return value == rhs; &#125;       \\</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01738" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1738"><Highlight kind="preprocessor">        bool operator&lt;(const &#95;type &amp;rhs) const &#123; return value &lt; rhs.value; &#125;   \\</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01739" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1739"><Highlight kind="preprocessor">        &#95;base value;                                                           \\</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01740" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1740"><Highlight kind="preprocessor">        using BaseType = &#95;base;                                                \\</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01741" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1741"><Highlight kind="preprocessor">    &#125;;</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01742" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1742"><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight><Highlight kind="comment"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01743" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1743"><Highlight kind="comment">///</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01744" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1744"><Highlight kind="comment">/// Use these types instead of uintXX&#95;t in any mapping to have</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01745" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1745"><Highlight kind="comment">/// its yaml output formatted as hexadecimal.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01746" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1746"><Highlight kind="comment">///</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01747" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1747"><Highlight kind="normal"><a href="#ab74df4ad631bb362ad7d41fd875f0481">LLVM&#95;YAML&#95;STRONG&#95;TYPEDEF</a>(uint8&#95;t, Hex8)</Highlight></CodeLine>
